Inject post-Pandoc vs. pre-generate Markdown include

| | Inject post-Pandoc | Pre-generate include |
|---|---|---|
| **How** | Bash/sed rewrites the built HTML after Pandoc | Bash generates a `_nav.html` fragment, passed to Pandoc via `--include-before-body` |
| **Reliability** | Fragile — depends on Pandoc's exact HTML output structure; breaks if Pandoc changes its wrapping | Stable — Pandoc owns the final render, the fragment is just injected cleanly |
| **Complexity** | Parsing HTML with sed is messy and error-prone | One bash loop to generate the fragment, one extra flag per Pandoc call |
| **Maintenance** | Hard to debug when it breaks | Easy — fragment is a plain HTML file you can inspect |
| **Verdict** | Avoid | **Use this** |

**Recommendation: pre-generate.** One bash loop extracts titles from frontmatter, writes `_nav_en.html` (and `_nav_nl.html`), each Pandoc call gets `--include-before-body _nav_en.html`. Zero manual work, zero fragility.

